individual_exchanges.speaker: Duke_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Merchant of Syracusa plead no more I am not partial to infringe our laws The enmity and discord which of late Sprung from the rancorous outrage of your duke To merchants our well-dealing countrymen Who wanting guilders to redeem their lives Have sealed his rigorous statutes with their bloods Excludes all pity from our threat’ning looks For since the mortal and intestine jars ’Twixt thy seditious countrymen and us It hath in solemn synods been decreed Both by the Syracusians and ourselves To admit no traffic to our adverse towns Nay more if any born at Ephesus Be seen at Syracusian marts and fairs Again if any Syracusian born Come to the bay of Ephesus he dies His goods confiscate to the Duke’s dispose Unless a thousand marks be levièd To quit the penalty and to ransom him Thy substance valued at the highest rate Cannot amount unto a hundred marks Therefore by law thou art condemned to die

individual_exchanges.speaker: Egeon_Err
individual_exchanges.text: A heavier task could not have been imposed Than I to speak my griefs unspeakable Yet that the world may witness that my end Was wrought by nature not by vile offense I’ll utter what my sorrow gives me leave In Syracusa was I born and wed Unto a woman happy but for me And by me had not our hap been bad With her I lived in joy Our wealth increased By prosperous voyages I often made To Epidamium till my factor’s death And the great care of goods at random left Drew me from kind embracements of my spouse From whom my absence was not six months old Before herself almost at fainting under The pleasing punishment that women bear Had made provision for her following me And soon and safe arrivèd where I was There had she not been long but she became A joyful mother of two goodly sons And which was strange the one so like the other As could not be distinguished but by names That very hour and in the selfsame inn A mean woman was deliverèd Of such a burden male twins both alike Those for their parents were exceeding poor I bought and brought up to attend my sons My wife not meanly proud of two such boys Made daily motions for our home return Unwilling I agreed Alas too soon We came aboard A league from Epidamium had we sailed Before the always-wind-obeying deep Gave any tragic instance of our harm But longer did we not retain much hope For what obscurèd light the heavens did grant Did but convey unto our fearful minds A doubtful warrant of immediate death Which though myself would gladly have embraced Yet the incessant weepings of my wife Weeping before for what she saw must come And piteous plainings of the pretty babes That mourned for fashion ignorant what to fear Forced me to seek delays for them and me And this it was for other means was none The sailors sought for safety by our boat And left the ship then sinking-ripe to us My wife more careful for the latter-born Had fastened him unto a small spare mast Such as seafaring men provide for storms To him one of the other twins was bound Whilst I had been like heedful of the other The children thus disposed my wife and I Fixing our eyes on whom our care was fixed Fastened ourselves at either end the mast And floating straight obedient to the stream Was carried towards Corinth as we thought At length the sun gazing upon the earth Dispersed those vapors that offended us And by the benefit of his wished light The seas waxed calm and we discoverèd Two ships from far making amain to us Of Corinth that of Epidaurus this But ere they came O let me say no more Gather the sequel by that went before

individual_exchanges.speaker: Egeon_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O had the gods done so I had not now Worthily termed them merciless to us For ere the ships could meet by twice five leagues We were encountered by a mighty rock Which being violently borne upon Our helpful ship was splitted in the midst So that in this unjust divorce of us Fortune had left to both of us alike What to delight in what to sorrow for Her part poor soul seeming as burdenèd With lesser weight but not with lesser woe Was carried with more speed before the wind And in our sight they three were taken up By fishermen of Corinth as we thought At length another ship had seized on us And knowing whom it was their hap to save Gave healthful welcome to their shipwracked guests And would have reft the fishers of their prey Had not their bark been very slow of sail And therefore homeward did they bend their course Thus have you heard me severed from my bliss That by misfortunes was my life prolonged To tell sad stories of my own mishaps

individual_exchanges.text: And for the sake of them thou sorrowest for Do me the favor to dilate at full What have befall’n of them and thee till now

individual_exchanges.speaker: Egeon_Err
individual_exchanges.text: My youngest boy and yet my eldest care At eighteen years became inquisitive After his brother and importuned me That his attendant so his case was like Reft of his brother but retained his name Might bear him company in the quest of him Whom whilst I labored of a love to see I hazarded the loss of whom I loved Five summers have I spent in farthest Greece Roaming clean through the bounds of Asia And coasting homeward came to Ephesus Hopeless to find yet loath to leave unsought Or that or any place that harbors men But here must end the story of my life And happy were I in my timely death Could all my travels warrant me they live

individual_exchanges.speaker: Duke_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Hapless Egeon whom the fates have marked To bear the extremity of dire mishap Now trust me were it not against our laws Against my crown my oath my dignity Which princes would they may not disannul My soul should sue as advocate for thee But though thou art adjudgèd to the death And passèd sentence may not be recalled But to our honor’s great disparagement Yet will I favor thee in what I can Therefore merchant I’ll limit thee this day To seek thy life by beneficial help Try all the friends thou hast in Ephesus Beg thou or borrow to make up the sum And live If no then thou art doomed to die Jailer take him to thy custody

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant1_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Therefore give out you are of Epidamium Lest that your goods too soon be confiscate This very day a Syracusian merchant Is apprehended for arrival here And not being able to buy out his life According to the statute of the town Dies ere the weary sun set in the west There is your money that I had to keep

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant1_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Therefore give out you are of Epidamium Lest that your goods too soon be confiscate This very day a Syracusian merchant Is apprehended for arrival here And not being able to buy out his life According to the statute of the town Dies ere the weary sun set in the west There is your money that I had to keep

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go bear it to the Centaur where we host And stay there Dromio till I come to thee Within this hour it will be dinnertime Till that I’ll view the manners of the town Peruse the traders gaze upon the buildings And then return and sleep within mine inn For with long travel I am stiff and weary Get thee away

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go bear it to the Centaur where we host And stay there Dromio till I come to thee Within this hour it will be dinnertime Till that I’ll view the manners of the town Peruse the traders gaze upon the buildings And then return and sleep within mine inn For with long travel I am stiff and weary Get thee away

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Many a man would take you at your word And go indeed having so good a mean

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Many a man would take you at your word And go indeed having so good a mean

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: A trusty villain sir that very oft When I am dull with care and melancholy Lightens my humor with his merry jests What will you walk with me about the town And then go to my inn and dine with me

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant1_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I am invited sir to certain merchants Of whom I hope to make much benefit I crave your pardon Soon at five o’clock Please you I’ll meet with you upon the mart And afterward consort you till bedtime My present business calls me from you now

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Farewell till then I will go lose myself And wander up and down to view the city

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant1_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Sir I commend you to your own content

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: He that commends me to mine own content Commends me to the thing I cannot get I to the world am like a drop of water That in the ocean seeks another drop Who falling there to find his fellow forth Unseen inquisitive confounds himself So I to find a mother and a brother In quest of them unhappy lose myself Enter Dromio of Ephesus Here comes the almanac of my true date What now How chance thou art returned so soon

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Returned so soon Rather approached too late The capon burns the pig falls from the spit The clock hath strucken twelve upon the bell My mistress made it one upon my cheek She is so hot because the meat is cold The meat is cold because you come not home You come not home because you have no stomach You have no stomach having broke your fast But we that know what ’tis to fast and pray Are penitent for your default today

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Stop in your wind sir Tell me this I pray Where have you left the money that I gave you

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O sixpence that I had o’ Wednesday last To pay the saddler for my mistress’ crupper The saddler had it sir I kept it not

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I am not in a sportive humor now Tell me and dally not where is the money We being strangers here how dar’st thou trust So great a charge from thine own custody

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I pray you jest sir as you sit at dinner I from my mistress come to you in post If I return I shall be post indeed For she will scour your fault upon my pate Methinks your maw like mine should be your clock And strike you home without a messenger

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Come Dromio come these jests are out of season Reserve them till a merrier hour than this Where is the gold I gave in charge to thee

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: To me sir Why you gave no gold to me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Come on sir knave have done your foolishness And tell me how thou hast disposed thy charge

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: My charge was but to fetch you from the mart Home to your house the Phoenix sir to dinner My mistress and her sister stays for you

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Now as I am a Christian answer me In what safe place you have bestowed my money Or I shall break that merry sconce of yours That stands on tricks when I am undisposed Where is the thousand marks thou hadst of me

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I have some marks of yours upon my pate Some of my mistress’ marks upon my shoulders But not a thousand marks between you both If I should pay your Worship those again Perchance you will not bear them patiently

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Thy mistress’ marks What mistress slave hast thou

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Your Worship’s wife my mistress at the Phoenix She that doth fast till you come home to dinner And prays that you will hie you home to dinner

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What wilt thou flout me thus unto my face Being forbid There take you that sir knave

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What mean you sir For God’s sake hold your hands Nay an you will not sir I’ll take my heels

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Upon my life by some device or other The villain is o’erraught of all my money They say this town is full of cozenage As nimble jugglers that deceive the eye Dark-working sorcerers that change the mind Soul-killing witches that deform the body Disguisèd cheaters prating mountebanks And many suchlike liberties of sin If it prove so I will be gone the sooner I’ll to the Centaur to go seek this slave I greatly fear my money is not safe

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Neither my husband nor the slave returned That in such haste I sent to seek his master Sure Luciana it is two o’clock

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Perhaps some merchant hath invited him And from the mart he’s somewhere gone to dinner Good sister let us dine and never fret A man is master of his liberty Time is their master and when they see time They’ll go or come If so be patient sister

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why should their liberty than ours be more

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Because their business still lies out o’ door

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Look when I serve him so he takes it ill

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O know he is the bridle of your will

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: There’s none but asses will be bridled so

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why headstrong liberty is lashed with woe There’s nothing situate under heaven’s eye But hath his bound in earth in sea in sky The beasts the fishes and the wingèd fowls Are their males’ subjects and at their controls Man more divine the master of all these Lord of the wide world and wild wat’ry seas Endued with intellectual sense and souls Of more preeminence than fish and fowls Are masters to their females and their lords Then let your will attend on their accords

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: This servitude makes you to keep unwed

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not this but troubles of the marriage bed

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: But were you wedded you would bear some sway

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ere I learn love I’ll practice to obey

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: How if your husband start some otherwhere

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Till he come home again I would forbear

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Patience unmoved No marvel though she pause They can be meek that have no other cause A wretched soul bruised with adversity We bid be quiet when we hear it cry But were we burdened with like weight of pain As much or more we should ourselves complain So thou that hast no unkind mate to grieve thee With urging helpless patience would relieve me But if thou live to see like right bereft This fool-begged patience in thee will be left

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Well I will marry one day but to try Here comes your man Now is your husband nigh

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Say is your tardy master now at hand

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Say is your tardy master now at hand

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay he’s at two hands with me and that my two ears can witness

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay he’s at two hands with me and that my two ears can witness

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Say didst thou speak with him Know’st thou his mind

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Say didst thou speak with him Know’st thou his mind

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ay ay he told his mind upon mine ear Beshrew his hand I scarce could understand it

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ay ay he told his mind upon mine ear Beshrew his hand I scarce could understand it

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Spake he so doubtfully thou couldst not feel his meaning

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Spake he so doubtfully thou couldst not feel his meaning

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay he struck so plainly I could too well feel his blows and withal so doubtfully that I could scarce understand them

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay he struck so plainly I could too well feel his blows and withal so doubtfully that I could scarce understand them

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: But say I prithee is he coming home It seems he hath great care to please his wife

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: But say I prithee is he coming home It seems he hath great care to please his wife

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why mistress sure my master is horn mad

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why mistress sure my master is horn mad

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Horn mad thou villain

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Horn mad thou villain

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I mean not cuckold mad But sure he is stark mad When I desired him to come home to dinner He asked me for a thousand marks in gold ’Tis dinnertime quoth I My gold quoth he Your meat doth burn quoth I My gold quoth he Will you come quoth I My gold quoth he Where is the thousand marks I gave thee villain The pig quoth I is burned My gold quoth he My mistress sir quoth I Hang up thy mistress I know not thy mistress Out on thy mistress

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I mean not cuckold mad But sure he is stark mad When I desired him to come home to dinner He asked me for a thousand marks in gold ’Tis dinnertime quoth I My gold quoth he Your meat doth burn quoth I My gold quoth he Will you come quoth I My gold quoth he Where is the thousand marks I gave thee villain The pig quoth I is burned My gold quoth he My mistress sir quoth I Hang up thy mistress I know not thy mistress Out on thy mistress

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Quoth who

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Quoth who

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Quoth my master I know quoth he no house no wife no mistress So that my errand due unto my tongue I thank him I bare home upon my shoulders For in conclusion he did beat me there

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Quoth my master I know quoth he no house no wife no mistress So that my errand due unto my tongue I thank him I bare home upon my shoulders For in conclusion he did beat me there

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go back again thou slave and fetch him home

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go back again thou slave and fetch him home

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go back again and be new beaten home For God’s sake send some other messenger

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go back again and be new beaten home For God’s sake send some other messenger

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Back slave or I will break thy pate across

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Back slave or I will break thy pate across

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: And he will bless that cross with other beating Between you I shall have a holy head

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: And he will bless that cross with other beating Between you I shall have a holy head

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Hence prating peasant Fetch thy master home

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Hence prating peasant Fetch thy master home

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Am I so round with you as you with me That like a football you do spurn me thus You spurn me hence and he will spurn me hither If I last in this service you must case me in leather

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Am I so round with you as you with me That like a football you do spurn me thus You spurn me hence and he will spurn me hither If I last in this service you must case me in leather

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Fie how impatience loureth in your face

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: His company must do his minions grace Whilst I at home starve for a merry look Hath homely age th’ alluring beauty took From my poor cheek Then he hath wasted it Are my discourses dull Barren my wit If voluble and sharp discourse be marred Unkindness blunts it more than marble hard Do their gay vestments his affections bait That’s not my fault he’s master of my state What ruins are in me that can be found By him not ruined Then is he the ground Of my defeatures My decayèd fair A sunny look of his would soon repair But too unruly deer he breaks the pale And feeds from home Poor I am but his stale

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Self-harming jealousy fie beat it hence

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Unfeeling fools can with such wrongs dispense I know his eye doth homage otherwhere Or else what lets it but he would be here Sister you know he promised me a chain Would that alone o’ love he would detain So he would keep fair quarter with his bed I see the jewel best enamelèd Will lose his beauty Yet the gold bides still That others touch and often touching will Wear gold yet no man that hath a name By falsehood and corruption doth it shame Since that my beauty cannot please his eye I’ll weep what’s left away and weeping die

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: How many fond fools serve mad jealousy

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: The gold I gave to Dromio is laid up Safe at the Centaur and the heedful slave Is wandered forth in care to seek me out By computation and mine host’s report I could not speak with Dromio since at first I sent him from the mart See here he comes Enter Dromio of Syracuse How now sir Is your merry humor altered As you love strokes so jest with me again You know no Centaur You received no gold Your mistress sent to have me home to dinner My house was at the Phoenix Wast thou mad That thus so madly thou didst answer me

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What answer sir When spake I such a word

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Even now even here not half an hour since

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I did not see you since you sent me hence Home to the Centaur with the gold you gave me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Villain thou didst deny the gold’s receipt And told’st me of a mistress and a dinner For which I hope thou felt’st I was displeased

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I am glad to see you in this merry vein What means this jest I pray you master tell me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Yea dost thou jeer and flout me in the teeth Think’st thou I jest Hold take thou that and that

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Hold sir for God’s sake Now your jest is earnest Upon what bargain do you give it me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Because that I familiarly sometimes Do use you for my fool and chat with you Your sauciness will jest upon my love And make a common of my serious hours When the sun shines let foolish gnats make sport But creep in crannies when he hides his beams If you will jest with me know my aspect And fashion your demeanor to my looks Or I will beat this method in your sconce

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Sconce call you it So you would leave battering I had rather have it a head An you use these blows long I must get a sconce for my head and ensconce it too or else I shall seek my wit in my shoulders But I pray sir why am I beaten

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Dost thou not know

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nothing sir but that I am beaten

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Shall I tell you why

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ay sir and wherefore for they say every why hath a wherefore

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why first for flouting me and then wherefore for urging it the second time to me

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Was there ever any man thus beaten out of season When in the why and the wherefore is neither rhyme nor reason Well sir I thank you

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Thank me sir for what

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir for this something that you gave me for nothing

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I’ll make you amends next to give you nothing for something But say sir is it dinnertime

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: No sir I think the meat wants that I have

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: In good time sir what’s that

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Basting

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Well sir then ’twill be dry

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: If it be sir I pray you eat none of it

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Your reason

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Lest it make you choleric and purchase me another dry basting

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Well sir learn to jest in good time There’s a time for all things

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I durst have denied that before you were so choleric

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: By what rule sir

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir by a rule as plain as the plain bald pate of Father Time himself

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Let’s hear it

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: There’s no time for a man to recover his hair that grows bald by nature

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: May he not do it by fine and recovery

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Yes to pay a fine for a periwig and recover the lost hair of another man

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why is Time such a niggard of hair being as it is so plentiful an excrement

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Because it is a blessing that he bestows on beasts and what he hath scanted men in hair he hath given them in wit

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why but there’s many a man hath more hair than wit

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not a man of those but he hath the wit to lose his hair

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why thou didst conclude hairy men plain dealers without wit

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: The plainer dealer the sooner lost Yet he loseth it in a kind of jollity

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: For what reason

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: For two and sound ones too

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay not sound I pray you

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Sure ones then

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay not sure in a thing falsing

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Certain ones then

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Name them

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: The one to save the money that he spends in tiring the other that at dinner they should not drop in his porridge

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: You would all this time have proved there is no time for all things

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry and did sir namely e’en no time to recover hair lost by nature

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: But your reason was not substantial why there is no time to recover

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Thus I mend it Time himself is bald and therefore to the world’s end will have bald followers

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I knew ’twould be a bald conclusion But soft who wafts us yonder

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ay ay Antipholus look strange and frown Some other mistress hath thy sweet aspects I am not Adriana nor thy wife The time was once when thou unurged wouldst vow That never words were music to thine ear That never object pleasing in thine eye That never touch well welcome to thy hand That never meat sweet-savored in thy taste Unless I spake or looked or touched or carved to thee How comes it now my husband O how comes it That thou art then estrangèd from thyself Thyself I call it being strange to me That undividable incorporate Am better than thy dear self’s better part Ah do not tear away thyself from me For know my love as easy mayst thou fall A drop of water in the breaking gulf And take unmingled thence that drop again Without addition or diminishing As take from me thyself and not me too How dearly would it touch thee to the quick Shouldst thou but hear I were licentious And that this body consecrate to thee By ruffian lust should be contaminate Wouldst thou not spit at me and spurn at me And hurl the name of husband in my face And tear the stained skin off my harlot brow And from my false hand cut the wedding ring And break it with a deep-divorcing vow I know thou canst and therefore see thou do it I am possessed with an adulterate blot My blood is mingled with the crime of lust For if we two be one and thou play false I do digest the poison of thy flesh Being strumpeted by thy contagion Keep then fair league and truce with thy true bed I live distained thou undishonorèd

individual_exchanges.text: Plead you to me fair dame I know you not In Ephesus I am but two hours old As strange unto your town as to your talk Who every word by all my wit being scanned Wants wit in all one word to understand

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: How ill agrees it with your gravity To counterfeit thus grossly with your slave Abetting him to thwart me in my mood Be it my wrong you are from me exempt But wrong not that wrong with a more contempt Come I will fasten on this sleeve of thine She takes his arm Thou art an elm my husband I a vine Whose weakness married to thy stronger state Makes me with thy strength to communicate If aught possess thee from me it is dross Usurping ivy brier or idle moss Who all for want of pruning with intrusion Infect thy sap and live on thy confusion

individual_exchanges.speaker: Balthasar_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Have patience sir O let it not be so Herein you war against your reputation And draw within the compass of suspect Th’ unviolated honor of your wife Once this your long experience of her wisdom Her sober virtue years and modesty Plead on her part some cause to you unknown And doubt not sir but she will well excuse Why at this time the doors are made against you Be ruled by me depart in patience And let us to the Tiger all to dinner And about evening come yourself alone To know the reason of this strange restraint If by strong hand you offer to break in Now in the stirring passage of the day A vulgar comment will be made of it And that supposèd by the common rout Against your yet ungallèd estimation That may with foul intrusion enter in And dwell upon your grave when you are dead For slander lives upon succession Forever housèd where it gets possession

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: You have prevailed I will depart in quiet And in despite of mirth mean to be merry I know a wench of excellent discourse Pretty and witty wild and yet too gentle There will we dine This woman that I mean My wife but I protest without desert Hath oftentimes upbraided me withal To her will we to dinner To Angelo Get you home And fetch the chain by this I know ’tis made Bring it I pray you to the Porpentine For there’s the house That chain will I bestow Be it for nothing but to spite my wife Upon mine hostess there Good sir make haste Since mine own doors refuse to entertain me I’ll knock elsewhere to see if they’ll disdain me

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: And may it be that you have quite forgot A husband’s office Shall Antipholus Even in the spring of love thy love-springs rot Shall love in building grow so ruinous If you did wed my sister for her wealth Then for her wealth’s sake use her with more kindness Or if you like elsewhere do it by stealth Muffle your false love with some show of blindness Let not my sister read it in your eye Be not thy tongue thy own shame’s orator Look sweet speak fair become disloyalty Apparel vice like virtue’s harbinger Bear a fair presence though your heart be tainted Teach sin the carriage of a holy saint Be secret-false What need she be acquainted What simple thief brags of his own attaint ’Tis double wrong to truant with your bed And let her read it in thy looks at board Shame hath a bastard fame well managèd Ill deeds is doubled with an evil word Alas poor women make us but believe Being compact of credit that you love us Though others have the arm show us the sleeve We in your motion turn and you may move us Then gentle brother get you in again Comfort my sister cheer her call her wife ’Tis holy sport to be a little vain When the sweet breath of flattery conquers strife

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Sweet mistress what your name is else I know not Nor by what wonder you do hit of mine Less in your knowledge and your grace you show not Than our Earth’s wonder more than Earth divine Teach me dear creature how to think and speak Lay open to my earthy gross conceit Smothered in errors feeble shallow weak The folded meaning of your words’ deceit Against my soul’s pure truth why labor you To make it wander in an unknown field Are you a god Would you create me new Transform me then and to your power I’ll yield But if that I am I then well I know Your weeping sister is no wife of mine Nor to her bed no homage do I owe Far more far more to you do I decline O train me not sweet mermaid with thy note To drown me in thy sister’s flood of tears Sing Siren for thyself and I will dote Spread o’er the silver waves thy golden hairs And as a bed I’ll take them and there lie And in that glorious supposition think He gains by death that hath such means to die Let love being light be drownèd if she sink

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What are you mad that you do reason so

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not mad but mated how I do not know

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: It is a fault that springeth from your eye

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: For gazing on your beams fair sun being by

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Gaze when you should and that will clear your sight

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: As good to wink sweet love as look on night

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why call you me love Call my sister so

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Thy sister’s sister

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: That’s my sister

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: No It is thyself mine own self’s better part Mine eye’s clear eye my dear heart’s dearer heart My food my fortune and my sweet hope’s aim My sole Earth’s heaven and my heaven’s claim

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: All this my sister is or else should be

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Call thyself sister sweet for I am thee Thee will I love and with thee lead my life Thou hast no husband yet nor I no wife Give me thy hand

individual_exchanges.speaker: Luciana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O soft sir Hold you still I’ll fetch my sister to get her goodwill

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Why how now Dromio Where runn’st thou so fast

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Do you know me sir Am I Dromio Am I your man Am I myself

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Thou art Dromio thou art my man thou art thyself

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I am an ass I am a woman’s man and besides myself

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What woman’s man And how besides thyself

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir besides myself I am due to a woman one that claims me one that haunts me one that will have me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What claim lays she to thee

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir such claim as you would lay to your horse and she would have me as a beast not that I being a beast she would have me but that she being a very beastly creature lays claim to me

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What is she

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: A very reverend body ay such a one as a man may not speak of without he say sir-reverence I have but lean luck in the match and yet is she a wondrous fat marriage

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: How dost thou mean a fat marriage

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir she’s the kitchen wench and all grease and I know not what use to put her to but to make a lamp of her and run from her by her own light I warrant her rags and the tallow in them will burn a Poland winter If she lives till doomsday she’ll burn a week longer than the whole world

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What complexion is she of

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Swart like my shoe but her face nothing like so clean kept For why She sweats A man may go overshoes in the grime of it

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: That’s a fault that water will mend

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: No sir ’tis in grain Noah’s flood could not do it

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What’s her name

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nell sir but her name and three quarters that’s an ell and three quarters will not measure her from hip to hip

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Then she bears some breadth

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: No longer from head to foot than from hip to hip She is spherical like a globe I could find out countries in her

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: In what part of her body stands Ireland

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Marry sir in her buttocks I found it out by the bogs

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where Scotland

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I found it by the barrenness hard in the palm of the hand

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where France

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: In her forehead armed and reverted making war against her heir

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where England

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I looked for the chalky cliffs but I could find no whiteness in them But I guess it stood in her chin by the salt rheum that ran between France and it

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where Spain

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Faith I saw it not but I felt it hot in her breath

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where America the Indies

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O sir upon her nose all o’erembellished with rubies carbuncles sapphires declining their rich aspect to the hot breath of Spain who sent whole armadas of carracks to be ballast at her nose

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Where stood Belgia the Netherlands

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O sir I did not look so low To conclude this drudge or diviner laid claim to me called me Dromio swore I was assured to her told me what privy marks I had about me as the mark of my shoulder the mole in my neck the great wart on my left arm that I amazed ran from her as a witch And I think if my breast had not been made of faith and my heart of steel She had transformed me to a curtal dog and made me turn i’ th’ wheel

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Go hie thee presently Post to the road An if the wind blow any way from shore I will not harbor in this town tonight If any bark put forth come to the mart Where I will walk till thou return to me If everyone knows us and we know none ’Tis time I think to trudge pack and be gone

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: As from a bear a man would run for life So fly I from her that would be my wife

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: There’s none but witches do inhabit here And therefore ’tis high time that I were hence She that doth call me husband even my soul Doth for a wife abhor But her fair sister Possessed with such a gentle sovereign grace Of such enchanting presence and discourse Hath almost made me traitor to myself But lest myself be guilty to self wrong I’ll stop mine ears against the mermaid’s song

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Master Antipholus

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Ay that’s my name

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I know it well sir Lo here’s the chain I thought to have ta’en you at the Porpentine The chain unfinished made me stay thus long

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What is your will that I shall do with this

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What please yourself sir I have made it for you

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Made it for me sir I bespoke it not

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not once nor twice but twenty times you have Go home with it and please your wife withal And soon at supper time I’ll visit you And then receive my money for the chain

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: I pray you sir receive the money now For fear you ne’er see chain nor money more

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: You are a merry man sir Fare you well

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: What I should think of this I cannot tell But this I think there’s no man is so vain That would refuse so fair an offered chain I see a man here needs not live by shifts When in the streets he meets such golden gifts I’ll to the mart and there for Dromio stay If any ship put out then straight away

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant2_Err
individual_exchanges.text: You know since Pentecost the sum is due And since I have not much importuned you Nor now I had not but that I am bound To Persia and want guilders for my voyage Therefore make present satisfaction Or I’ll attach you by this officer

individual_exchanges.speaker: Merchant2_Err
individual_exchanges.text: You know since Pentecost the sum is due And since I have not much importuned you Nor now I had not but that I am bound To Persia and want guilders for my voyage Therefore make present satisfaction Or I’ll attach you by this officer

individual_exchanges.speaker: Angelo_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Even just the sum that I do owe to you Is growing to me by Antipholus And in the instant that I met with you He had of me a chain At five o’clock I shall receive the money for the same Pleaseth you walk with me down to his house I will discharge my bond and thank you too

individual_exchanges.text: Not that Adam that kept the Paradise but that Adam that keeps the prison he that goes in the calf’s skin that was killed for the Prodigal he that came behind you sir like an evil angel and bid you forsake your liberty

individual_exchanges.text: I understand thee not

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: No Why ’tis a plain case he that went like a bass viol in a case of leather the man sir that when gentlemen are tired gives them a sob and ’rests them he sir that takes pity on decayed men and gives them suits of durance he that sets up his rest to do more exploits with his mace than a morris-pike

individual_exchanges.text: What thou mean’st an officer

individual_exchanges.text: Why sir I brought you word an hour since that the bark Expedition put forth tonight and then were you hindered by the sergeant to tarry for the hoy Delay Here are the angels that you sent for to deliver you

individual_exchanges.speaker: Courtesan_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Now out of doubt Antipholus is mad Else would he never so demean himself A ring he hath of mine worth forty ducats And for the same he promised me a chain Both one and other he denies me now The reason that I gather he is mad Besides this present instance of his rage Is a mad tale he told today at dinner Of his own doors being shut against his entrance Belike his wife acquainted with his fits On purpose shut the doors against his way My way is now to hie home to his house And tell his wife that being lunatic He rushed into my house and took perforce My ring away This course I fittest choose For forty ducats is too much to lose

individual_exchanges.speaker: Abbess_Err
individual_exchanges.text: And thereof came it that the man was mad The venom clamors of a jealous woman Poisons more deadly than a mad dog’s tooth It seems his sleeps were hindered by thy railing And thereof comes it that his head is light Thou sayst his meat was sauced with thy upbraidings Unquiet meals make ill digestions Thereof the raging fire of fever bred And what’s a fever but a fit of madness Thou sayest his sports were hindered by thy brawls Sweet recreation barred what doth ensue But moody and dull melancholy Kinsman to grim and comfortless despair And at her heels a huge infectious troop Of pale distemperatures and foes to life In food in sport and life-preserving rest To be disturbed would mad or man or beast The consequence is then thy jealous fits Hath scared thy husband from the use of wits

individual_exchanges.speaker: Adriana_Err
individual_exchanges.text: May it please your Grace Antipholus my husband Who I made lord of me and all I had At your important letters this ill day A most outrageous fit of madness took him That desp’rately he hurried through the street With him his bondman all as mad as he Doing displeasure to the citizens By rushing in their houses bearing thence Rings jewels anything his rage did like Once did I get him bound and sent him home Whilst to take order for the wrongs I went That here and there his fury had committed Anon I wot not by what strong escape He broke from those that had the guard of him And with his mad attendant and himself Each one with ireful passion with drawn swords Met us again and madly bent on us Chased us away till raising of more aid We came again to bind them Then they fled Into this abbey whither we pursued them And here the Abbess shuts the gates on us And will not suffer us to fetch him out Nor send him forth that we may bear him hence Therefore most gracious duke with thy command Let him be brought forth and borne hence for help

individual_exchanges.text: Long since thy husband served me in my wars And I to thee engaged a prince’s word When thou didst make him master of thy bed To do him all the grace and good I could Go some of you knock at the abbey gate And bid the Lady Abbess come to me I will determine this before I stir

individual_exchanges.speaker: Messenger_Err
individual_exchanges.text: O mistress mistress shift and save yourself My master and his man are both broke loose Beaten the maids a-row and bound the doctor Whose beard they have singed off with brands of fire And ever as it blazed they threw on him Great pails of puddled mire to quench the hair My master preaches patience to him and the while His man with scissors nicks him like a fool And sure unless you send some present help Between them they will kill the conjurer

individual_exchanges.speaker: AntipholusOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: My liege I am advisèd what I say Neither disturbed with the effect of wine Nor heady-rash provoked with raging ire Albeit my wrongs might make one wiser mad This woman locked me out this day from dinner That goldsmith there were he not packed with her Could witness it for he was with me then Who parted with me to go fetch a chain Promising to bring it to the Porpentine Where Balthasar and I did dine together Our dinner done and he not coming thither I went to seek him In the street I met him And in his company that gentleman He points to Second Merchant There did this perjured goldsmith swear me down That I this day of him received the chain Which God He knows I saw not for the which He did arrest me with an officer I did obey and sent my peasant home For certain ducats He with none returned Then fairly I bespoke the officer To go in person with me to my house By th’ way we met My wife her sister and a rabble more Of vile confederates Along with them They brought one Pinch a hungry lean-faced villain A mere anatomy a mountebank A threadbare juggler and a fortune-teller A needy hollow-eyed sharp-looking wretch A living dead man This pernicious slave Forsooth took on him as a conjurer And gazing in mine eyes feeling my pulse And with no face as ’twere outfacing me Cries out I was possessed Then all together They fell upon me bound me bore me thence And in a dark and dankish vault at home There left me and my man both bound together Till gnawing with my teeth my bonds in sunder I gained my freedom and immediately Ran hither to your Grace whom I beseech To give me ample satisfaction For these deep shames and great indignities

individual_exchanges.speaker: Egeon_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not know my voice O time’s extremity Hast thou so cracked and splitted my poor tongue In seven short years that here my only son Knows not my feeble key of untuned cares Though now this grainèd face of mine be hid In sap-consuming winter’s drizzled snow And all the conduits of my blood froze up Yet hath my night of life some memory My wasting lamps some fading glimmer left My dull deaf ears a little use to hear All these old witnesses I cannot err Tell me thou art my son Antipholus

individual_exchanges.speaker: Abbess_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Renownèd duke vouchsafe to take the pains To go with us into the abbey here And hear at large discoursèd all our fortunes And all that are assembled in this place That by this sympathizèd one day’s error Have suffered wrong Go keep us company And we shall make full satisfaction Thirty-three years have I but gone in travail Of you my sons and till this present hour My heavy burden ne’er deliverèd The Duke my husband and my children both And you the calendars of their nativity Go to a gossips’ feast and go with me After so long grief such nativity

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: There is a fat friend at your master’s house That kitchened me for you today at dinner She now shall be my sister not my wife

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Methinks you are my glass and not my brother I see by you I am a sweet-faced youth Will you walk in to see their gossiping

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Not I sir You are my elder

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: That’s a question How shall we try it

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfSyracuse_Err
individual_exchanges.text: We’ll draw cuts for the signior Till then lead thou first

individual_exchanges.speaker: DromioOfEphesus_Err
individual_exchanges.text: Nay then thus We came into the world like brother and brother And now let’s go hand in hand not one before another
